RABIES STATISTICS- USA (TEXAS): AUGUST 1999
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Rabies statistics - USA (Texas): July 1999 991009092716
Rabies statistics - USA (Texas): June1999 990820143420
Rabies statistics - USA (Texas): May 1999 990715213707
Rabies statistics - USA (Texas): November 1998 990116221429
Date: Wed, 17 Nov 1999 09:36:40 -0600 (CST)
From: Pam Wilson <Pam.Wilson@tdh.state.tx.us>

During August, there were 6 cases of canine rabies in South Texas. All of
these cases, including 4 dogs, 1 cat, and 1 coyote, occurred in Willacy
County. These were the first cases of canine rabies in South Texas since
early April 1999 and the first cases of canine rabies in Willacy County
since late February 1999. There were 4 people exposed to the rabid dogs and
3 people exposed to the rabid cats; they all received postexposure
treatment. Additionally, there were 8 dogs and 4 cats exposed to the rabid
dogs. Of the exposed animals, one dog was currently vaccinated and received
postexposure treatment; the 7 other dogs and the 4 cats were euthanized.
Additionally, 18 horses were vaccinated against rabies as a precaution
after a rabid coyote was found on the premises of the horse barn. To date,
no cases of canine rabies have been reported north of the South Texas Oral
Rabies Vaccination (ORVP) drop-zone for coyotes.
In West-Central Texas, there were 3 cases of gray fox rabies in the
following counties: Kerr (1 fox), Sutton (1 fox), and Val Verde (1 fox). To
date, no cases of gray fox rabies have been reported beyond the boundaries
of the original ORVP drop-zone for gray foxes.
There were 37 cases of rabies in animals statewide, including:
13 bats, 8 skunks, 6 cats, 4 dogs, 3 foxes, 1 cow, 1 coyote, 1 horse,
Laboratories in Texas that conducted rabies testing on submitted specimens
include: Texas Department of Health, Bureau of Laboratories, Austin; El
Paso City-County Health Department Laboratory; City of Houston Health
Department, Bureau of Laboratory Services; and San Antonio Metropolitan
Health District Laboratory.
--
Pam Wilson, RVT, MEd, CHES
Texas Department of Health
Zoonosis Control Division
e-mail: Pam.Wilson@tdh.state.tx.us
